<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,222,607]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
The collection of Nepalese specimens included seven specimens with wing venation similar to that of the 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,222,246]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[180,360,259,283]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[180,360,259,283]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Bittacus indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[374,442,258,282]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1045,1068]" captionTargetBox="[202,1363,712,967]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[176,1410,642,1024]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 5. Bittacus indicus. Holotype, left forewing. Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278725/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
Fig. 
<number box="[426,442,258,282]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[513,611,258,282]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">holotype</typeStatus>
is missing its abdomen and the details of the terminalia are unknown. The terminalia of the male specimen of the Nepalese 
<taxonomicName box="[703,816,294,319]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[703,816,294,319]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
match those of the 
<typeStatus box="[1039,1136,295,319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">paratype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1174,1316,295,319]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taraiensis">
<emphasis box="[1174,1316,295,319]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. taraiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Thus, the slight variation in Sc crossvein location of 
<taxonomicName box="[628,769,332,355]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taraiensis">
<emphasis box="[628,769,332,355]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. taraiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[823,935,331,355]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[823,935,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are deemed to be normal variation. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rust" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" refString="Rust, M. K. &amp; Byers, G. W. (1976) The Mecoptera of India and adjacent regions. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 51, 19 - 90." type="journal article" year="1976">
Rust and Byers (
<number box="[233,292,366,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" value="1976.0">1976</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
discussed these variations and acknowledged that it was probable that these two species were synonyms. Clarification required a male with an intact terminalia, which is now at hand, and so I consider 
<taxonomicName box="[1295,1435,404,427]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taraiensis">
<emphasis box="[1295,1435,404,427]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. taraiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName box="[447,559,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[447,559,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">B. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The elongate proctiger of this species suggests an affinity with many oriental species.
</paragraph>
